Package: cjdiag
Title: Diagnostic Tools for Conjoint Survey Experiments
Version: 0.2.1
Authors@R:
    person("David", "Karpa", , "davidfkarpa@gmail.com", role = c("aut", "cre", "cph"),
           comment = c(ORCID = "0000-0002-4327-4269"))
Description: Tools for attribute-level importance and attendance in conjoint
    survey experiments — which attribute levels drive choices, how they rank,
    and which ones respondents ignore. Provides five methods via a unified
    interface: random forests (Breiman (2001) <doi:10.1023/A:1010933404324>)
    to identify which attribute levels matter most, 'CART' decision trees to
    reveal how respondents structure their decisions hierarchically,
    penalized regression via 'hierNet' to separate genuine drivers from
    noise (Bien and Tibshirani (2014) <doi:10.1214/14-AOAS757>), nested
    marginal means to uncover the order in which attribute levels settle
    choices (Dill, Howlett and Mueller-Crepon (2024) <doi:10.1017/pan.2024.12>),
    and per-respondent marginal R-squared to detect which attributes each
    respondent actually used (Jenke, Bansak, Hainmueller and Hangartner
    (2021) <doi:10.1017/pan.2020.11>). Supports level-specific and
    attribute-level resolution with publication-ready 'ggplot2' visualizations.
